title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland Auditorium Arena on 1979-12-28
lineage: CD -> Adobe Audition v3.0 -> Samplitude Professional v11.2 -> FLAC
description:
Set 1

Sugaree, Mama Tried-> Mexicali Blues, Row Jimmy, It's All Over Now, High Time, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Alabama Getaway-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Terrapin Station-> Playin' In The Band-> Drums-> Uncle John's Band-> I Need A Miracle-> Bertha-> Good Lovin', E: Casey Jones, E: One More Saturday Night*

*Second Encore

reviews.review_text: totd reccomends Totd sent me here, damn fine show. All hail Charlie Miller and totd.

my favorite This is just my thinking but to me this is far and away the best intro to The Music never Stopped. The 1st few nights of New Years runs were usually better then the big night itself. I think because there was so much energy in the air which leads to something like this.  
All hail the band themselves sure we have been lucky to have good quality music from tapers but is the band.
 Set list is average but the playing is above average

Greatest Alabama Also needs to be mentioned that this Alabama > Greatest transition is the Leshiest of them all. You can feel the audience explode. Sometimes it's just a "stop/start" but this one was hot.

The whole show and the entire Oakland 79' XMAS/NYE run is proof that 79' is underrated. Any head that dismisses the band after Keith and Donna should refer to this run before being so sure. 

Thanks for the upgrade. Wish I could figure out how to download the confangled thing... ;)

Get this. For some reason, I wrote off this whole run awhile back. But I was looking for something different, and I found this. Wow. I don't know what I was thinking earlier. This show is amazing. Someone in a previous review mentioned the intro to The Music Never Stopped, which is cool, but the entire song is amazing. I've been checking out different versions of this song lately, and this might be the best one yet. 

The energy gets going early on and doesn't quit. 

By the way, this show was released as Road Trips Vol. 3, No. 1.

Stellar Quality & Playing This is a Gem. It sounds great, like really great and the playing is superb. Becoming a big fan of '79. Jerry's voice is still smooth. Tiger is ripping. Brent keys have that "Go To Heaven" sound. The setlists are pretty decent as well. This is a show you can play start to finish without any glaring flaws. Kudos to Charlie Miller for yet another awesome SBD.
